      "writtenOn": "2016-05-09T09:37:24Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "frankly I\u0027m very uncomfortable with the idea of potentially-uninitialized pointers in class instances. It\u0027s very easy to extend a class with a new constructor and/or method and forget that the pointer isn\u0027t properly initialized.\n\nI doubt that pointer construction to NULL is really a performance issue, compared to say copying std::shared_ptr instances, I\u0027d rather see the use of default initialization values in class member declarations instead. What do you think?",
      "revId": "0568fdab0a2f387d34c4e9d043320ddcaccef188",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
